[Maps of Australia can be seen at http://maps.unomaha.edu/peterson/funda/MapLinks/Australia/Australia_files/image001.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4882640,11143. Swan Hill can be seen on the map at https://goo.gl/KsHLfP.

There are a number of lessons to be learnt from this Australian sheep anthrax outbreak. The most obvious one is to not ignore unexpected livestock deaths. By delaying, this outbreak went from one animal dead to 34, and this then put neighbouring livestock at risk. Hopefully the owners of any livestock subject to secondary outbreaks do not have lawyers.

Secondly this outbreak was forecast by a posting last July 2016, which covered a PLoS publication on GARP [genetic algorithm for rule-set prediction model system] niche modelling _Bacillus anthracis_ ecology in Australia; see 22 Jun 2016: Anthrax - Australia: niche modeling of historic distribution 20160622.4302780. The full reference is

Barro AS, Fegan M, Moloney B, et al. Redefining the Australian anthrax belt: modeling the ecological niche and predicting the geographic distribution of _Bacillus anthracis_. PLoS Negl Trop Dis. 2016; 10(6): e0004689. doi: 10.1371/journal.pntd.0004689
http://journals.plos.org/plosntds/article?id=10.1371/journal.pntd.0004689

And if you bring up this paper check out figure 3, "Predicted geographic distribution of _Bacillus anthracis_ in Australia based on GARP ecological niche modeling" and you will see that outbreaks in this part of Victoria were predicted. This is one of the valuable uses of GARP niche modelling. It tells one clearly where any surveillance programmes must be concentrated. And this is not the 1st time that such a model was shown to be correct and of value.

In my experience of this disease over many years, sheep anthrax deaths are commonly overlooked initially. I suspect it is because of the low value of individual sheep. The threshold for reporting is around 6 to a dozen deaths for flocks of some 100 ewes. For flocks of some 1000 ewes it starts getting reported at 2 dozen deaths, at least in South Africa. In Australia it seems that the reporting threshold approaches 3 dozen deaths. For peasant farmers with just a few dozen sheep their problem is that they can be invisible to their government veterinarians and response to any reports may be slow, if at all. - Mod.MHJ]
